1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:16,000
 Welcome to C Programming for Everybody. My name is Charles Severance. This is my reading of the 1978 C Programming book written by Brian Kernigan and Dennis Ritchie. At times, I add my own interpretation of the material from a historical perspective.

2
00:00:16,000 --> 00:00:26,000
 Chapter 8. The Unix System Interface. The material in this chapter is concerned with the interface between C programs and the Unix operating system.

3
00:00:26,000 --> 00:00:39,000
 Since most C programs are on Unix systems, this should be helpful to a majority of the readers. Even if you see on a different machine, however, you should be able to glean more insight into C programming from studying these examples.

4
00:00:39,000 --> 00:00:53,000
 This chapter is divided into three major areas - input/output, file system, and a storage allocator. The first two parts assume a modest familiarity with the external characteristics of Unix.

5
00:00:53,000 --> 00:01:07,000
 Chapter 7 was concerned with a system interface that is uniform across a variety of operating systems. On any particular system, the routines of the standard library have to be written in terms of the I/O facilities that are actually available on the host system.

6
00:01:07,000 --> 00:01:20,000
 In the next few sections, we'll describe the basic system entry points for I/O on the Unix operating system and illustrate how parts of the standard library can be implemented with them.

7
00:01:20,000 --> 00:01:37,000
 As an aside, the dual nature of C and Unix has been on display throughout the book, and while this chapter is called the Unix System Interface, in a sense, it's less about Unix itself and very much about why C is such a great programming language.

8
00:01:37,000 --> 00:01:52,000
 Let me explain. Before Unix and C became the norm, operating systems and operating system utilities - those commands we used interactively and in batch jobs - were quite often written in the assembly language of the computer which it was supporting.

9
00:01:52,000 --> 00:02:07,000
 Often, there were not well documented API calls between utilities in assembly language and the assembly language which implemented the operating system. Smart vendor programmers would just look at the operating system code and write their utility code to work with it.

10
00:02:07,000 --> 00:02:33,000
 This section shows that a language that has features like structures, arrays, pointers, preprocessor, and unions was sufficiently rich so that we could document all the intricate interfaces with an operating system using a relatively high level language, and then we could write our utility code, like CAD, in a high level language as well.

11
00:02:33,000 --> 00:02:41,000
 In this chapter, the authors are almost shouting, "Quit using assembly language to build your operating system and utility code!"

12
00:02:41,000 --> 00:03:04,000
 Further, they are showing us examples designed to answer the question that might come from programmers used to the old ways like, "Can we do X, Y, Z, and C?" The authors' emphatic answer in the increasingly intricate code samples is, "C is not a toy language that's only something used by a few AT&T computer scientists in a research lab."

13
00:03:04,000 --> 00:03:12,000
 If you're doing serious system stuff that needs maximum performance and readability and reliability, use C.

14
00:03:12,000 --> 00:03:23,000
 This chapter shows C in all its glory and shows why it was such an important language to enable the world of technology we have 40 years later.

15
00:03:23,000 --> 00:03:43,000
 At the end of the chapter, we'll talk a little bit about how C enabled the creation of easier-to-use programming languages and why it was so important to invent C-inspired languages like Python, PHP, and Java once C became the established systems programming language.

16
00:03:43,000 --> 00:03:58,000
 Section 8.1. File Descriptors. In the Unix operating system, all input and output is done by reading or writing files, because all peripheral devices, even the user's terminal, are files in the file system.

17
00:03:58,000 --> 00:04:06,000
 This means that a single homogeneous interface handles all communications between a program and peripheral devices.

18
00:04:06,000 --> 00:04:16,000
 In the most general case, before reading or writing a file, it is necessary to inform the system of your intent to do so, a process called opening the file.

19
00:04:16,000 --> 00:04:23,000
 If you're going to write on a file, it may also be necessary to create it. The system checks for your right to do so.

20
00:04:23,000 --> 00:04:32,000
 Does the file exist? Do you have permission to access it? And if all is well, returns to the program a small positive integer called the file descriptor.

21
00:04:32,000 --> 00:04:39,000
 Whenever IO is to be done on the file, the file descriptor is used instead of the name to identify the file.

22
00:04:39,000 --> 00:04:49,000
 This is roughly analogous to the use of read(5, ...) and write(6, ...) in Fortran.

23
00:04:49,000 --> 00:04:57,000
 All information about an open file is maintained by the system. The user refers to the file only by the file descriptor.

24
00:04:57,000 --> 00:05:05,000
 Since input and output involving the user's terminal is so common, special arrangements exist to make this convenient.

25
00:05:05,000 --> 00:05:19,000
 When the command interpreter, the shell, runs a program, it opens three files with files descriptors 0, 1, and 2, called the standard input, standard output, and standard error output.

26
00:05:19,000 --> 00:05:30,000
 All of these are normally connected with a terminal, so if a program reads file descriptor 0 and writes to file descriptors 1 and 2, it can do terminal IO without worrying about opening the files.

27
00:05:30,000 --> 00:05:51,000
 The user of the program can redirect input/output to and from files with less than and greater than. For example, prog less than in file greater than out file. In this case, the shell changes the default assignments for file descriptors 0 and 1 from the terminal to the named files.

28
00:05:51,000 --> 00:05:57,000
 Normally, file descriptor 2 remains attached to the terminal, so error messages can go there.

29
00:05:57,000 --> 00:06:09,000
 Similar observations hold if the input or output is associated with a pipe. In all cases, it must be noted that the file assignments are changed by the shell, not the program.

30
00:06:09,000 --> 00:06:18,000
 The program does not know where its input comes from, nor where its output goes, so long as it uses file 0 for input and 1 and 2 for out.

31
00:06:18,000 --> 00:06:32,000
 Section 8.2, Low Level IO, Read and Write. This lowest level of IO in Unix provides no buffering or any other services. It is, in fact, a direct entry into the operating system.

32
00:06:32,000 --> 00:06:40,000
 All input and output is done by two functions called read and write. For both, the first argument is a file descriptor.

33
00:06:40,000 --> 00:06:49,000
 The second argument is a buffer in your program where the data is to come from or go to. The third argument is the number of bytes to be transferred.

34
00:06:49,000 --> 00:07:11,000
 The calls are nread = read(fd, buff, n, semicolon) nwritten = write(fd, buff, n, semicolon) Each call returns a byte count, which is the number of bytes actually transferred.

35
00:07:11,000 --> 00:07:23,000
 On reading, the number of bytes returned may be less than the number asked for. A return value of 0 bytes implies n to file, and -1 indicates an error of some sort.

36
00:07:23,000 --> 00:07:34,000
 For writing, the return value is the actual number of bytes written. It is generally an error if this isn't equal to the supposed number that was asked to be written.

37
00:07:34,000 --> 00:07:51,000
 The number of bytes to be read or written is quite arbitrary. The two most common values are 1, which means one character at a time, or unbuffered, and 512, which corresponds to the physical block size on many early peripheral devices.

38
00:07:51,000 --> 00:07:59,000
 This latter size will be most efficient, but even a character at a time IO is not inordinately expensive.

39
00:07:59,000 --> 00:08:10,000
 Putting these facts together, we can write a simple program to copy its input to its output, the equivalent of a file copying program written for Chapter 1.

40
00:08:10,000 --> 00:08:19,000
 In Unix, this program will copy anything to anything, since input and output can be redirected to any file or device.

41
00:08:19,000 --> 00:08:28,000
 This example is on page 161 of the textbook, which you can view at www.cc4e.com/code.

42
00:08:28,000 --> 00:08:41,000
 Pound include STDIO.h. Pound to find buff size 512. This is the best size for PDP-11 Unix. Modern computers should probably be larger.

