68
00:12:12,000 --> 00:12:18,000
 Section 8.3, open, create, close, unlink.

69
00:12:18,000 --> 00:12:23,000
 Create is not create, it's create without the e, so I'll just call it create for now.

70
00:12:23,000 --> 00:12:32,000
 Other than the default standard input and output and error files, you must explicitly open files in order to read or write them.

71
00:12:32,000 --> 00:12:36,000
 There are two system entry points for this, open and create.

72
00:12:36,000 --> 00:12:46,000
 Open is rather like the fopen, discussed in chapter 7, except that instead of returning a file pointer, it returns a file descriptor, which is just an int.

73
00:12:46,000 --> 00:12:56,000
 int fd, semicolon, fd = open, open paren, name, comma, rwmode, close paren, semicolon.

74
00:12:56,000 --> 00:13:01,000
 As with fopen, the name argument is a character string corresponding to the external file name.

75
00:13:01,000 --> 00:13:09,000
 The access mode argument is different, however. rwmode is 0 for read, 1 for write, and 2 for read/write access.

76
00:13:09,000 --> 00:13:15,000
 Open returns -1 if any error occurs, otherwise it returns a valid file descriptor.

77
00:13:15,000 --> 00:13:18,000
 It is an error to open a file that does not exist.

78
00:13:18,000 --> 00:13:23,000
 The entry point, create, is provided to create new files or to rewrite old ones.

79
00:13:23,000 --> 00:13:29,000
 fd = create, open paren, name, comma, pmode, close paren, semicolon.

80
00:13:29,000 --> 00:13:35,000
 Returns a file descriptor if it was able to create the file name, and -1 if not.

81
00:13:35,000 --> 00:13:39,000
 If the file already exists, create will truncate it to 0 length.

82
00:13:39,000 --> 00:13:43,000
 It is not an error to create a file that already exists.

83
00:13:43,000 --> 00:13:49,000
 If the file is brand new, create creates it with the protection mode specified in the pmode argument.

84
00:13:49,000 --> 00:13:56,000
 In the Unix file system, there are 9 bits of protection information associated with each file,

85
00:13:56,000 --> 00:14:03,000
 controlling read, write, and execute permission for the owner of the file, for the owner's group, and for all others.

86
00:14:03,000 --> 00:14:10,000
 Thus, a 3-digit octal number is the most convenient format for specifying permissions.

87
00:14:10,000 --> 00:14:17,000
 For example, 0755 specifies read, write, and execute permission for the owner,

88
00:14:17,000 --> 00:14:22,000
 and read and execute permission for group and for everyone else.

89
00:14:22,000 --> 00:14:30,000
 To illustrate here, a simplified version of the Unix utility cp, a program that copies one file to another.

90
