 The function, unlink open paren file name, close paren, removes the file name from the file system.

111
00:18:11,000 --> 00:18:24,000
 Section 8.4, random access, seek and lseek. File I/O is normally sequential. Each read or write takes place at a position in the file right after the previous one.

112
00:18:24,000 --> 00:18:35,000
 When necessary, however, a file can be read or written in any arbitrary order. The system called lseek provides a way to move around in a file without actually reading or writing.

113
00:18:35,000 --> 00:18:47,000
 lseek, open paren fd, offset, origin, close paren semicolon, forces the current position in the file, whose descriptor is fd, to move to the position offset,

114
00:18:47,000 --> 00:18:55,000
 which is taken relative to the location specified by origin. Subsequent reading or writing will begin at that position.

115
00:18:55,000 --> 00:19:09,000
 Offset is a long, fd and origin are ints. Origin can be 0, 1, or 2 to specify that the offset is to be measured from the beginning, from current position, or from the end of file, respectively.

116
00:19:09,000 --> 00:19:26,000
 For example, to append to a file, seek to the end before writing. lseek, open paren, ft, comma, 0l, comma, 2, close paren semicolon, to get back to the beginning, i.e. rewind to the beginning.

117
00:19:26,000 --> 00:19:42,000
 lseek, open paren, fd, comma, 0l, comma, 0, parenthesis, semicolon. Note that the 0l argument could also be written as open paren long, close paren, 0.

118
00:19:42,000 --> 00:19:49,000
 With lseek, it's possible to treat files more or less like large arrays at the price of slower access.

119
00:19:49,000 --> 00:19:56,000
 For example, the following simple function reads any number of bytes from any arbitrary place in a file.

120
00:19:56,000 --> 00:20:19,000
 get, open paren, fd, comma, pause, comma, buff, comma, n, close paren; int, fd, comma, n, long, pause, semicolon; char, star, buff, semicolon; open curly brace; lseek, open parenthesis, fd, comma, pause, comma, 0, close paren, semicolon;

121
00:20:19,000 --> 00:20:29,000
 return, open paren, read, open paren, fd, comma, buff, comma, n, close paren, close paren, semicolon; close curly brace.

122
00:20:29,000 --> 00:20:50,000
 In pre-version 7 Unix, the basic entry point to the I/O system is called seek. Seek is identical to lseek, except that its offset argument is an int rather than a long. Accordingly, since PDP-11 integers only have 16 bits, the offset specified for seek is limited to 65,535.

123
00:20:50,000 --> 00:21:04,000
 For this reason, origin values of 3, 4, and 5 cause seek to multiply the given offset by 512, which is the number of bytes in one physical block on a PDP-11, and then interpret origin as if it were 0, 1, or 2, respectively.

124
00:21:04,000 --> 00:21:19,000
 Thus, to get to an arbitrary place in a large file requires two seeks. The first one selects the block, then one which has origin equal to 1, and then moves to the desired byte within the block.

125
00:21:19,000 --> 00:21:29,000
 Once again, we see C in Unix straddling a major improvement in computer hardware in 1978. The natural name for a function to randomly move around a file would be seek.

126
00:21:29,000 --> 00:21:41,000
 But in early versions of Unix, seek took an integer as the offset, but on small word computers like PDP-11 have an integer that can't represent a large number, so seek used a complex set of rules to handle larger files.

127
00:21:41,000 --> 00:21:50,000
 The only logical thing was to have the offset be a long, and then for upwards compatibility make a new function called elseek that we use to this day.

128
00:21:50,000 --> 00:21:57,000
 Section 8.5, an example implementation of fopen and getc.

129
00:21:57,000 --> 00:22:06,000
 Let us illustrate how some of these pieces fit together by showing an implementation of the standard library routines fopen and getc on the PDP-11.

130
00:22:06,000 --> 00:22:12,000
 Recall that files in the standard library are described by file pointers rather than file descriptors.

131
00:22:12,000 --> 00:22:17,000
 A file pointer is a pointer to a structure that contains several pieces of information about the file.

132
00:22:17,000 --> 00:22:30,000
 A pointer to a buffer, so the file can read in large chunks, a count of the number of characters left in the buffer, a pointer to the next character position in the buffer, and some flags describing read/write mode and the file descriptor.

133
00:22:30,000 --> 00:22:41,000
 The data structure that describes a file is contained in the file stdio.h, which must be included by #include in any source file that uses routines from the standard library.

134
00:22:41,000 --> 00:22:44,000
 It is also included by functions in that library.

135
