 getc masks the character with 0, 3, 7, 7, which defeats the sign extension done by the pdp11 and ensures that all characters will be positive.

155
00:26:17,000 --> 00:26:29,000
 Although we will not discuss any details, we've included the definition of putc to show that it operates in much the same way as getc, calling a function flushbuff when its output buffer is full.

156
00:26:29,000 --> 00:26:33,000
 The function fopen and fillbuff can now be written.

157
00:26:33,000 --> 00:26:41,000
 Most of fopen is concerned with getting a file opened and positioned at the right place, and setting the flag bits to indicate the proper state.

158
00:26:41,000 --> 00:26:48,000
 fopen does not allocate any buffer space. This is done by fillbuff when the file is first read.

159
00:26:48,000 --> 00:26:56,000
 You can look at this sample code from page 167 at www.cc4e.com/code.

160
00:26:56,000 --> 00:27:04,000
 I won't read it here because it's pretty long and intricate, so you'll have to go watch it online or view it online.

161
00:27:04,000 --> 00:27:18,000
 Back to the text. The function fillbuff is rather more complicated. The main complexity lies in the fact that fillbuff attempts to permit access to the file even though there may not be enough memory to buffer the I/O.

162
00:27:18,000 --> 00:27:30,000
 If the space for a new buffer cannot be obtained from calloc, all is well. If not, fillbuff does unbuffered I/O using a single character stored in a private array.

163
00:27:30,000 --> 00:27:36,000
 The first call to getC for a particular file finds a count of zero, which forces a call of fillbuff.

164
00:27:36,000 --> 00:27:41,000
 If fillbuff finds that the file is not open for reading, it returns EOF immediately.

165
00:27:41,000 --> 00:27:51,000
 Otherwise, it tries to allocate a large buffer and, failing that, a single character buffer, setting the buffering information in flag appropriately.

166
00:27:51,000 --> 00:28:01,000
 Once the buffer is established, fillbuff simply calls read to fill it and sets the count and pointers, and returns the character at the beginning of the buffer.

167
00:28:01,000 --> 00:28:08,000
 Subsequent calls to fillbuff will find a buffer already allocated. The only remaining loose end is how everything gets started.

168
00:28:08,000 --> 00:28:24,000
 The array I/O/B must be defined and initialized for stdin, stdout, and stderr. File I/O/B and close square bracket equals open curly brace.

169
00:28:24,000 --> 00:28:49,000
 Open curly brace, null, comma, zero, comma, null, comma, underscore, read, comma, zero, comma, close curly brace, comma, and that's the stdin. The next one is open curly brace, null, comma, zero, comma, null, comma, underscore, write, comma, one, comma, close curly brace, comma, and that's the stdout definition, the sub one position.

170
00:28:49,000 --> 00:29:05,000
 And then the next one is open curly brace, null, comma, zero, comma, null, comma, underscore, write, vertical bar, underscore, unbuff, comma, two, close print, and that is the standard error entry, close curly brace, semicolon.

171
00:29:05,000 --> 00:29:16,000
 The initialization of the flag part of the structure shows that stdin is to be read, stdout is to be written, and stderr is to be written unbuffered.

172
00:29:16,000 --> 00:29:21,000
 Section 8.6, example, listing directories.

173
00:29:21,000 --> 00:29:36,000
 I would note that the sample code in section 8.6 shows how we can write applications like LS to interact with directories in a Unix file system. However, the code in this section is not portable to modern Unix systems, so we'll leave the code as it is in this section.

174
00:29:36,000 --> 00:29:47,000
 It's a good idea to read the code and get an outline of how to work with directories on Unix. If you want to write code to handle directories, you'll need to consult more modern documentation.

175
00:29:47,000 --> 00:30:16,000
 Given the complexity of the code in this section, we are not going to include it in the copy of this book in this particular media. Similarly, section 8.7, example, a storage allocator consists of a lot of really complex code, and so we will leave that for you to see online at www.cc4e.com/book/chap08.md.

176
00:30:16,000 --> 00:30:33,000
 Dynamic memory is hard. Modern languages like Python, Ruby, and Java give us high-level objects like strings, lists, and dictionaries. These structures automatically expand and contract and can be copied into a temporary variable, used, and then discarded.

177
00:30:33,000 --> 00:30:50,000
 Modern languages depend on efficient memory allocation. A problem when dynamic memory is heavily used is the fragmentation of the free space. You can get to the point where you have plenty of memory, but each of the free memory areas is so small that you can't allocate a new memory block.

178
00:30:50,000 --> 00:31:06,000
 When this happens, the runtime implementations of these systems run a step called garbage collection, where everything pauses and free areas are moved around to make sure that the free memory is in a few large contiguous areas rather than many small non-contiguous areas.

179
00:31:06,000 --> 00:31:15,000
 Language developers have been improving garbage collection algorithms for the past 40 years, and there is still much work to do.

180
00:31:15,000 --> 00:31:30,000
 Now that the authors have established all the reasons that make C the ideal portable systems programming language, which I hardly agree with, it's time to talk about where C comes up short as a general purpose language for those of us not working on the source code to Linux.

181
00:31:30,000 --> 00:31:45,000
 The most challenging aspect of C is the lack of dynamic structures that we can use without the need to carefully allocate, use without regard to the length of dynamically allocated memory, and not worry about calling C-free every single time we call C-alloc.

182
00:31:45,000 --> 00:31:57,000
 If a programmer without strong programming skills, a good understanding of a testing regimen, and a proper defensive programming attitude is let loose in C, they will invariably write poor code.

183
00:31:57,000 --> 00:32:07,000
 Their C code will make poor use of resources, run the system out of memory, or produce code that is riddled with security holes and bugs that seem to randomly appear.

184
00:32:07,000 --> 00:32:13,000
 A decade after C emerged and became popular, Guido van Rossum designed a language called Python.

185
00:32:13,000 --> 00:32:28,000
 It was one of a number of languages that was built using C, and added an object-oriented layer that greatly simplified writing programs that use dynamic memory, and added guardrails so programmers did not unintentionally write dangerous or insecure code.

186
00:32:28,000 --> 00:32:43,000
 The key value-add features that make Python more appropriate for general purpose programming are the String object, List object, and Dict object that handle all aspects of creating and using variables and collections of variables.

187
00:32:43,000 --> 00:32:49,000
 The book has one footnote, "Unix is a trademark of Bell Laboratories."

188
00:32:49,000 --> 00:32:51,000
 But, of course, there's more.

189
00:32:51,000 --> 00:32:58,000
 Actually, the trademark for Unix is no longer owned by AT&T, it is owned by the Open Group. But that is a story for another day.

190
00:32:58,000 --> 00:33:11,000
 The Unix story arc includes AT&T Unix, Berkeley Software Distribution, which we call BSD, Sun Microsystems, Minix, Linux, the Open Software Foundation, Unix International, and others.

191
00:33:11,000 --> 00:33:22,000
 The short version of that story is that AT&T Unix was poised to take over the world as an open source product long before the words "open source" were ever spoken.

192
00:33:22,000 --> 00:33:42,000
 AT&T should have and could have defined open source and changed everything by the early 1980s, except for a few AT&T intellectual property lawyers. It took over a decade for computer science to pivot away from a nearly exclusive focus on C and AT&T Unix.

193
00:33:42,000 --> 00:33:53,000
 The Linux operating system was open source from its inception and became the standard bearer for Unix-like operating systems and continues to be the way most of us encounter "Unix."

194
00:33:53,000 --> 00:34:01,000
 It is almost certain that the computer that served this media to you runs Linux. But that is a story for another time.

195
00:34:01,000 --> 00:34:11,000
 In 1978, Unix and C were in their glory days and showed the entire computer science field and technology industry the right way forward.

196
00:34:11,000 --> 00:34:26,000
 From that point forward, hardware could evolve independently from software. With the systems programming language and operating systems patterns sorted, the previous 40 years have seen an amazing innovation in hardware capability and performance.

197
00:34:26,000 --> 00:34:43,000
 This 1978 C programming book by Brian W. Kernigan and Dennis M. Ritchie was the big bang moment for modern computing and computer science. We owe them a debt of gratitude for making whatever we do today possible.

198
00:34:43,000 --> 00:34:58,000
 If you have made it to the end of this chapter in this book as your narrator, I would like to congratulate and thank you. It has been an honor to record and narrate a book of such historical significance for you. Cheers.

199
00:34:58,000 --> 00:35:20,000
 This work is based on the 1978 C programming book written by Brian W. Kernigan and Dennis M. Ritchie. Their book is copyright all rights reserved by AT&T, but is used in this work under fair use because of the book's historical and scholarly significance, its lack of availability, and the lack of an accessible version of the book.

200
00:35:20,000 --> 00:35:40,000
 The book is augmented in places to help understand its right place in historical context amidst the major changes of the 1970s and 1980s as computer science evolved from a hardware-first vendor-centered approach to a software-centered approach where portable operating systems and applications written in C could run on any hardware.

201
00:35:40,000 --> 00:36:00,000
 This is not the ideal book to learn C programming because the 1978 edition does not reflect the modern C language. Using an obsolete book gives us an opportunity to take students back in time and understand how the C language was evolving as it laid the groundwork for a future with portable applications.

